Recursive common table expressions: hierarchies and graph traversal.

Some questions are inherently recursive: give me every direct and indirect report of a manager, give me the full ancestor chain of a category, give me all nodes reachable from a graph vertex. With recursive is how sequel expresses them.

A recursive common table expression has two parts, glued together by union all. The anchor is a non-recursive query that produces the starting rows. The recursive step is a query that joins the expression's name back to itself, producing the next layer.

The engine evaluates the anchor once, then evaluates the recursive step repeatedly, feeding the new rows back in, until the recursive step produces zero rows. Without a clear termination condition, the recursion never ends, so give the expression a depth column you can cap if you don't fully trust the data.
